{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_2boccioni_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280604768/1946060701/0182.xml":{"full_text":"95 Cents Hour Oliered\nIn 40 Per Cent ol Jobs\nNow Listed by USES\nForty per cent of the 7,000 job\nopenings listed with the United\nStates Employment Service here\noffer 95 cents an hour or better, the\nagency reported today.\nIn its monthly news letter to em\nployers, the employment service\nnoted that total unemployment in\nthe Washington area remains \u201cfair\nly high\u201d\u2014somewhere between 20,\n000 and 25,000\u2014but the rate of ris\ning unemployment is \"definitely\nslackening.\"\nThe news letter predicted that\nwith the peak of military discharges\npast, unemployment will decline, be\nginning in midsummer.\nThree-fourths of the jobless men\nare veterans, according to employ\nment service figures. Men outnum\nber women more than three to one\namong Washington job seekers, the\nnews letter noted.\nJobs and workers are still hard\nto bring together the report said.\nFormer war workers and discharged\nveterans, \u201cfaced w'ith high living\ncosts here, shy at many job offers\npaying less than they had expected,\u201d\nthe news letter pointed out. On the\nother hand, the letter added, em\nployers are seeking skills which few\nof the job seekers have gained. The\nbulk of the vacancies listed with\nthe USES are in clerical, sales and\nskilled work.\nThe report noted that skilled\nworkers are available in the area,\nincluding machinists, welders, con\nstruction craftsmen, equipment op\nerators, truck drivers, radio repair\nmen, male office and payroll clerks,\nbut \"jobs offering less than $35 a\nweek do not attract them.\u201d\nThe news letter also reported that\ncivilian Government employment is\nstill rising here and that a growing\nnumber of larger private firms are\noffering systematic annual and sick\nleave programs, retirement plans,\ngroup hospitalization and other em\nploye benefits.\nBirths Reported\nJames and Juanita Adams, girl.\nRobert a